The 1-page school calendar can be found at https://www.milaca.k12.mn.us/sites/milaca.k12.mn.us/files/files/2021/2020-21%20Calendar%20-%20Approved.pdf

Thank you for your patience and understanding.

post_text: Interested in helping the students and shape the school district? Would you like the opportunity to have your voice heard on school district issues? Here's your chance! On the November 3 General Election ballot, there will be three school board vacancies! To apply, complete an affidavit of candidacy, (must be notarized) and submit your $2 filing fee to the District Office by 5:00 p.m. on August 11. Affidavit of candidacy can be downloaded at https://www.milaca.k12.mn.us/page/2549 or picked up in the District Office. #MilacaPride

post_text:
On the November 3, 2020 ballot there will be three school board seats with the terms expiring January 2025. The filing period to apply for school board is July 28 - August 11. The application materials can be picked up at the District Office, requested to be sent by mail, or are accessible on the district website at https://www.milaca.k12.mn.us/page/2549

If you are interested in becoming a school board member MSBA will be recorded a zoom meeting to cover basics such as how to file for the board, reasons to serve on the board — and reasons not to serve on a board, job duties of school boards, and how boards function as a team. This recording can be accessed at https://youtu.be/BhUZMzM2Vmo #MilacaPride

post_text:
Happy July 1st!

I want to introduce (or reintroduce) myself to the Milaca Community. My name is Dave Wedin and starting today I am superintendent of schools for the Milaca Public School District. I am excited to start in this new role and grateful to be entering my twelfth year working with the school district. I am humbled by the opportunity to continue serving the staff, students, and community of Milaca Public Schools.

As the picture shows, my family and I are super excited!

Go Wolves!

Did your child participate in free or reduced-price school meals? Minnesota is now offering funds for families of children ages 5 to 18 who qualify for free or reduced-price school meals. The new program, called Pandemic EBT (P-EBT), will provide up to $325 per child that families can use to purchase nutritious food for their household. Approximately 350,000 Minnesota children could benefit. Deadline to apply is June 30, 2020.

Learn more at www.mn.p-ebt.org

post_text:
Last Thursday, the ALC staff conducted a Graduation Convoy, stopping at each of the 16 graduates from the Milaca ALC homes to present them with a Certificate of Completion, official ALC hat, and a gift from the staff. The convoy covered some territory starting in Maple Grove (farthest south) and traveled to Bock (farthest east), Isle (farthest north), and ended in Foley (farthest east). This is the largest graduating class in Milaca ALC history!

The graduation ceremony was held remotely. To view the ceremony go to https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rGXm2jyjhKI&feature=youtu.be

Congratulations to these graduates and best of luck with your future endeavors! #MilacaPride

post_text: Every spring, the fifth, sixth, and seventh grade bands perform a concert demonstrating their growth over the year. Unfortunately, when the governor called the Stay at Home order, the bands were almost to their scheduled concert. Due to the order, the concert could not be held in the high school gym with the accompaniment of the entire band. However, the show must go on! During distance learning, students continued to practice at home. On April 16, students performed their concert songs for their families complete with an introduction provided by Mr. Garber and music track accompaniment, giving families the full band experience! Although it was not the typical spring concert, it was still a fun conclusion to the spring concert season. Of course, in true Mr. Garber style, students were encouraged to have ice cream after their performance! #MilacaPride

In honor of Earth Day, Ms. Hakes-Anderson's 4th grade class created a special poem! #MilacaPride

Earth Day Poem
~ Created by Ms. Hakes-Anderson’s 4th grade students

We help the Earth
We pick up your yard and we clean up the roads and our towns
We planted 4 new trees two years ago
We recycle
We clean up the ditch and our yard
We plant trees and clean up our ditches
We clean and recycle
We recycle, clean our yard, and use reusable grocery bags
We plant 🌲
We recycle
“WE” can all do these things for our Earth!

post_text:
REMINDER - Tonight at 8:30 p.m., Milaca Public Schools will be joining the "Be the Light" movement in which schools across the nation turn on stadium lights as a beacon of hope and better times ahead for our students, staff, and community. The Herb Claffy Stadium lights and scoreboard will be used to honor and recognize all our students - especially our 2020 Seniors and the great class and leaders they are!

With that in mind, we will also honor the “Stay at Home” order from Governor Walz and the social distancing guidelines established by the Minnesota Department of Health and the CDC. We ask if you drive to the school to see this event, you remain in your vehicle and remember social distancing guidelines. The stadium will remain locked for everyone’s safety, as this beacon of hope is meant to be experienced that way. #MilacaPride

On April 20 at 8:30 p.m., Milaca Public Schools will be joining the "Be the Light" movement in which schools across the nation turn on stadium lights as a beacon of hope and better times ahead for our students, staff, and community. The Herb Claffy Stadium lights and scoreboard will be used to honor and recognize all our students - especially our 2020 Seniors and the great class and leaders they are!

With that in mind, we will also honor the “Stay at Home” order from Governor Walz and the social distancing guidelines established by the Minnesota Department of Health and the CDC. We ask if you drive to the school to see this event, you remain in your vehicle and remember social distancing guidelines. The stadium will remain locked for everyone’s safety, as this beacon of hope is meant to be experienced that way. #MilacaPride

post_text:
Distance Learning will begin on Monday, March 30 and will go through May 4. Milaca Schools will begin the delivery of necessary school materials for students tomorrow, March 26. Materials will be delivered by bus during the regular meal drop off times (between 11:30 a.m. - 1:30 p.m.).

If families are not home during the drop-off, materials will be placed in the Town and Country Shopper mailbox. If families do not have a Town and Country Shopper mailbox, you may leave a tote with a cover or cooler by your stop and materials can be placed in the container.

This delivery will continue each week as needed.

Please contact the offices (Elementary at 320-982-7301 or High School at 320-982-7206) if you have any questions.

post_text:
In addition to meals being available at the Milaca High School cafeteria doors for curbside pick up, beginning Monday, March 23, meals will be available for delivery to bus stop locations. If your child does not currently ride a bus, the bus company will contact you with drop off details.

The meals are for children ages 18 and younger, are free of charge, and will include lunch for that day and breakfast for the following day. If you are interested in your children receiving these meals, please check your email or text message to sign up. The deadline to sign up is tomorrow, March 20 at 7:00 a.m., so we can plan accordingly.

post_text: Mr. Vesledahl’s Exploring Construction students built a barn style playhouse that was sold by auction at the Minneapolis Home and Garden show as a fundraiser for Habitat for Humanity. The students designed and built the playhouse from material that was donated by the Milaca Building Center. The winning bid was $600.00, which was donated to Habitat for Humanity. Eight schools participated in the fundraiser and raised over $5,000 for Habitat for Humanity. It was awesome experience. #MilacaPride

post_text:
The Milaca Agriculture department's greenhouse management class have completed their first maple syrup boil with the new evaporator system purchased through a grant from the MN DNR. Students have 18 silver maple trees tapped on the school campus, and have been collecting sap daily.

MHS welding students constructed an elevated stand for our sap container, which allows the sap to be gravity fed into a float box on the evaporator. Once the float boxes are adjusted properly, the system takes sap as needed.

In addition to the new evaporator, students also utilized a new vacuum filter to clean and bottle the syrup. The vacuum filter worked great!

A special thank you to Mr. Kiel and his applied technology classes for laser engraving our bottles! #MilacaPride
